TY  - JOUR
T1  - On the Informativeness of Descriptive Statistics for Structural Estimates
AU  - Andrews, Isaiah
AU  - Gentzkow, Matthew
AU  - Shapiro, Jesse M.
Y1  - 2020/11/01
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2020/11/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA16768
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
JA  - Econometrica
SP  - 2231
EP  - 2258
VL  - 88
IS  - 6
KW  - Local misspecification
KW  - transparency
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA16768
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We propose a way to formalize the relationship between descriptive analysis and structural estimation. A researcher reports an estimate ? of a structural quantity of interest c that is exactly or asymptotically unbiased under some base model. The researcher also reports descriptive statistics that estimate features ? of the distribution of the data that are related to c under the base model. A reader entertains a less restrictive model that is local to the base model, under which the estimate ? may be biased. We study the reduction in worst-case bias from a restriction that requires the reader's model to respect the relationship between c and ? specified by the base model. Our main result shows that the proportional reduction in worst-case bias depends only on a quantity we call the informativeness of for ?. Informativeness can be easily estimated even for complex models. We recommend that researchers report estimated informativeness alongside their descriptive analyses, and we illustrate with applications to three recent papers.
ER  - 

